messages.content:
So I have a ZkProgram which generates a proof, and i want to serialize that Proof with .toJson(). But from my logs, the actual proving of the circuit takes around 7 seconds, but the serialization into the json takes over 60 seconds. Tested on multiple machines. Should that be the case? What could be the issue here?
Am happy to share some code if someone wants to take a look
Ye would love to see an example
I think its the same operation as this? https://github.com/MinaProtocol/mina/blob/d594541e1ac03dffc08e2556d9ecfd763a351d87/src/lib/snarky_js_bindings/test_module/inductive-proofs.js#L134

messages.content: Yes
Do you know how long this example takes?
I’ll have to check once I am on my pc
But I doubt it takes 60s to serialise a proof into a json structure
I wrote that test just the other week with the latest snarkyjs branch
Maybe it’s something wrong with an earlier version
I’ll investigate when I get back to my pc
I´m on 0.7.3, so that shouldn´t be the case really
I´ll try to reproduce it into a small example
Ok I have isolated the issue to only occur when I execute the logic inside a web-server
In my case fastify
But that is so weird

Okay wow, so it turn out i used an instanceof in the workerlogic which checked the proof. And that seemed to have taken a long time to traverse the whole object. And the tictoc was not set properly so I thought it was the toJson() 😄
So now that the issue is fixed, I made a benchmark test and turns out that the proving of my ZkProgram takes around 40sec on a 10-core machine. Thats a lot isn´t it?
Depending on your setup and circuit size 40s sounds like something I would expect currently, ye
I ran a couple of benchmarks on popular cloud services with different instance sizes - 40s is pretty common
the sweet spot seems to be somewhere around 16core, while increasing the # of cores too much (64, 128, ...) wont give you any more benefits - it might even slow it down a tad
I see, yeah the circuit is pretty big, a Signature and 2 Witnesses + checks and computeRoot
Gonna have to wait for gregor to implement the *"low hanging fruits"* 😂
